&lt;p&gt;In the React snippet, we see the use of hooks to fetch data and update the state. In the Next.js version, the code is quite similar, but Next.js offers an alternative approach using &lt;code&gt;getServerSideProps&lt;/code&gt; or &lt;code&gt;getStaticProps&lt;/code&gt; for fetching data, which can improve performance and SEO.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h1&gt;Real-World Applications: The Impact of Next.js and React&lt;/h1&gt;&lt;p&gt;The digital landscape is dotted with a myriad of applications, each serving unique purposes but often built on a foundation of shared technologies. Two such technologies, Next.js and React, have become staples in the development community, powering a vast array of real-world applications. This blog post aims to shed light on the practical use cases of both Next.js and React, illustrating their versatility and impact in the industry.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2&gt;Next.js: Beyond the Basics&lt;span class="hx:absolute hx:-mt-20" id="nextjs-beyond-the-basics"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a href="#nextjs-beyond-the-basics" class="subheading-anchor" aria-label="Permalink for this section"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;Next.js, a framework for React, offers enhanced features like server-side rendering and static site generation, making it a go-to choice for various applications:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;E-commerce Platforms&lt;span class="hx:absolute hx:-mt-20" id="e-commerce-platforms"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a href="#e-commerce-platforms" class="subheading-anchor" aria-label="Permalink for this section"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;p&gt;Next.js shines in the e-commerce domain, where performance, SEO, and real-time updates are paramount. It supports dynamic content changes and handles high traffic effortlessly, making it ideal for online stores.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;Marketing Websites&lt;span class="hx:absolute hx:-mt-20" id="marketing-websites"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a href="#marketing-websites" class="subheading-anchor" aria-label="Permalink for this section"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;p&gt;From enterprise sites to portfolios, Next.js provides a robust solution for marketing purposes. Its SEO-friendly nature ensures higher visibility and reach for promotional content.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;Blogs&lt;span class="hx:absolute hx:-mt-20" id="blogs"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a href="#blogs" class="subheading-anchor" aria-label="Permalink for this section"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;p&gt;The framework&amp;rsquo;s static generation feature is perfect for blogs, optimizing content delivery and SEO, thereby attracting more readers and engagement.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;Entertainment Platforms&lt;span class="hx:absolute hx:-mt-20" id="entertainment-platforms"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a href="#entertainment-platforms" class="subheading-anchor" aria-label="Permalink for this section"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;p&gt;Heavyweights like Netflix and Twitch leverage Next.js to deliver content-rich experiences to millions of users daily, thanks to its efficient content delivery mechanisms.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;Community-Driven Web Apps&lt;span class="hx:absolute hx:-mt-20" id="community-driven-web-apps"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a href="#community-driven-web-apps" class="subheading-anchor" aria-label="Permalink for this section"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;p&gt;Next.js is well-suited for apps that require frequent content updates and new page creation, offering flexibility and speed in content delivery.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;News Applications&lt;span class="hx:absolute hx:-mt-20" id="news-applications"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a href="#news-applications" class="subheading-anchor" aria-label="Permalink for this section"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;p&gt;For platforms where timely content delivery is critical, Next.js provides the necessary infrastructure to ensure news reaches readers without delay.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;Documentation Websites&lt;span class="hx:absolute hx:-mt-20" id="documentation-websites"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a href="#documentation-websites" class="subheading-anchor" aria-label="Permalink for this section"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;p&gt;Next.js aids in creating comprehensive documentation websites, enhancing the developer experience and supporting software product sales.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;Booking and Auction Sites&lt;span class="hx:absolute hx:-mt-20" id="booking-and-auction-sites"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a href="#booking-and-auction-sites" class="subheading-anchor" aria-label="Permalink for this section"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;p&gt;The framework excels in environments demanding real-time updates, such as ticket sales and auctions, by delivering content swiftly across the globe.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2&gt;React: The UI Building Block&lt;span class="hx:absolute hx:-mt-20" id="react-the-ui-building-block"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a href="#react-the-ui-building-block" class="subheading-anchor" aria-label="Permalink for this section"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;React, on the other hand, is known for its component-based architecture, which has been employed in various scenarios:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;Marketplaces&lt;span class="hx:absolute hx:-mt-20" id="marketplaces"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a href="#marketplaces" class="subheading-anchor" aria-label="Permalink for this section"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;p&gt;Platforms like Airbnb utilize React to create seamless and interactive user interfaces for their marketplace applications.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;Virtual Reality Tours&lt;span class="hx:absolute hx:-mt-20" id="virtual-reality-tours"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a href="#virtual-reality-tours" class="subheading-anchor" aria-label="Permalink for this section"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;p&gt;Applications offering virtual tours, such as Transported, rely on React&amp;rsquo;s capabilities to manage complex UI interactions in real-time.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;Enterprise-Level Software&lt;span class="hx:absolute hx:-mt-20" id="enterprise-level-software"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a href="#enterprise-level-software" class="subheading-anchor" aria-label="Permalink for this section"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;p&gt;Companies like Atlassian build their software solutions with React, benefiting from its efficient UI rendering and data management.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;Social Media Platforms&lt;span class="hx:absolute hx:-mt-20" id="social-media-platforms"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a href="#social-media-platforms" class="subheading-anchor" aria-label="Permalink for this section"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;p&gt;Social media giants, including Facebook, harness React to handle dynamic content and interactive features, ensuring a smooth user experience.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;Streaming Services&lt;span class="hx:absolute hx:-mt-20" id="streaming-services"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a href="#streaming-services" class="subheading-anchor" aria-label="Permalink for this section"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;p&gt;Subscription-based services like Netflix use React to deliver their content-rich platforms, capitalizing on its fast rendering and state management features.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;Cyber Risk Management&lt;span class="hx:absolute hx:-mt-20" id="cyber-risk-management"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a href="#cyber-risk-management" class="subheading-anchor" aria-label="Permalink for this section"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;p&gt;Platforms like CyberCube employ React to manage and display complex data related to cyber risks, taking advantage of its component reusability and efficient updates.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In conclusion, both Next.js and React have carved out significant roles in the web development ecosystem, each bringing distinct advantages to the table. Next.js, with its focus on performance and SEO, is particularly well-suited for applications where content delivery speed is crucial. React&amp;rsquo;s component-based approach makes it a versatile choice for a wide range of applications, from simple interfaces to complex enterprise solutions. As the digital world continues to evolve, the real-world applications of these technologies will undoubtedly expand, further cementing their status as foundational tools for modern web development.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2&gt;Conclusion&lt;span class="hx:absolute hx:-mt-20" id="conclusion"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;a href="#conclusion" class="subheading-anchor" aria-label="Permalink for this section"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;Both Next.js and React offer unique advantages that cater to different project requirements. Next.js is ideal for applications that benefit from SSR and SSG, while React&amp;rsquo;s simplicity and flexibility make it suitable for a wide range of projects. Ultimately, the choice between Next.js and React depends on the specific needs of the project and the developer&amp;rsquo;s familiarity with these technologies. By understanding the pros and cons of each, developers can make informed decisions that align with their goals for optimal web application development..&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Mastering feature flagging with ReactJs, Golang, and Github Actions</title><link>https://acethecloud.com/blog/mastering-feature-flagging-with-reactjs-golang-and-github-actions/</link><pubDate>Thu, 09 Mar 2023 17:38:27 +0530</pubDate><guid>https://acethecloud.com/blog/mastering-feature-flagging-with-reactjs-golang-and-github-actions/</guid><description>
&lt;p&gt;Feature flagging is a technique used in software development to turn on and off certain features within an application, without requiring a full deployment. This can be useful for testing new features or providing different experiences to different groups of users. In this blog post, we will show you how to master feature flagging using ReactJs, Golang, and Github Actions.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Step 1: Define the feature flag&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The first step in mastering feature flagging is to define the flag. We can do this by creating a configuration file that contains all the feature flags for our application. For example, we can create a JSON file with the following content:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="hextra-code-block hx:relative hx:mt-6 hx:first:mt-0 hx:group/code"&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;div class="highlight"&gt;&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma"&gt;&lt;code class="language-json" data-lang="json"&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;{&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt; &lt;span class="nt"&gt;&amp;#34;featureA&amp;#34;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="kc"&gt;false&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;,&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt; &lt;span class="nt"&gt;&amp;#34;featureB&amp;#34;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="kc"&gt;true&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;}&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="hextra-code-copy-btn-container hx:opacity-0 hx:transition hx:group-hover/code:opacity-100 hx:flex hx:gap-1 hx:absolute hx:m-[11px] hx:right-0 hx:top-0"&gt;
&lt;button
class="hextra-code-copy-btn hx:group/copybtn hx:cursor-pointer hx:transition-all hx:active:opacity-50 hx:bg-primary-700/5 hx:border hx:border-black/5 hx:text-gray-600 hx:hover:text-gray-900 hx:rounded-md hx:p-1.5 hx:dark:bg-primary-300/10 hx:dark:border-white/10 hx:dark:text-gray-400 hx:dark:hover:text-gray-50"
title="Copy code"
aria-label="Copy code"
data-copied-label="Copied!"
&gt;
&lt;div class="hextra-copy-icon hx:group-[.copied]/copybtn:hidden hx:pointer-events-none hx:h-4 hx:w-4"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="hextra-success-icon hx:hidden hx:group-[.copied]/copybtn:block hx:pointer-events-none hx:h-4 hx:w-4"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/button&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The &lt;code&gt;featureA&lt;/code&gt; flag is set to &lt;code&gt;false&lt;/code&gt;, which means it is turned off, while the &lt;code&gt;featureB&lt;/code&gt; flag is set to &lt;code&gt;true&lt;/code&gt;, which means it is turned on.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Step 2: Implement the feature flag in ReactJs&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Now that we have defined the feature flag, we can use it in our ReactJs application. We can create a component that checks the value of the flag and displays the appropriate content. For example, we can create a &lt;code&gt;FeatureA&lt;/code&gt; component that displays a message if &lt;code&gt;featureA&lt;/code&gt; is turned on:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="hextra-code-block hx:relative hx:mt-6 hx:first:mt-0 hx:group/code"&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;div class="highlight"&gt;&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma"&gt;&lt;code class="language-javascript" data-lang="javascript"&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;&lt;span class="kr"&gt;import&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="nx"&gt;features&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="nx"&gt;from&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="s1"&gt;&amp;#39;./config.json&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;&lt;span class="kd"&gt;function&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="nx"&gt;FeatureA&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;()&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="p"&gt;{&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt; &lt;span class="k"&gt;if&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="p"&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="nx"&gt;features&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="nx"&gt;featureA&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;)&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="p"&gt;{&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt; &lt;span class="k"&gt;return&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="p"&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;&amp;lt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="nx"&gt;div&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;&amp;gt;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;&amp;lt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="nx"&gt;h1&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;&amp;gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="nx"&gt;Feature&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="nx"&gt;A&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="nx"&gt;is&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="nx"&gt;on&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;!&amp;lt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="err"&gt;/h1&amp;gt;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;&amp;lt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="err"&gt;/div&amp;gt;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt; &lt;span class="p"&gt;);&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt; &lt;span class="p"&gt;}&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt; &lt;span class="k"&gt;return&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="kc"&gt;null&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;}&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;&lt;span class="kr"&gt;export&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="k"&gt;default&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="nx"&gt;FeatureA&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="hextra-code-copy-btn-container hx:opacity-0 hx:transition hx:group-hover/code:opacity-100 hx:flex hx:gap-1 hx:absolute hx:m-[11px] hx:right-0 hx:top-0"&gt;
&lt;button
class="hextra-code-copy-btn hx:group/copybtn hx:cursor-pointer hx:transition-all hx:active:opacity-50 hx:bg-primary-700/5 hx:border hx:border-black/5 hx:text-gray-600 hx:hover:text-gray-900 hx:rounded-md hx:p-1.5 hx:dark:bg-primary-300/10 hx:dark:border-white/10 hx:dark:text-gray-400 hx:dark:hover:text-gray-50"
title="Copy code"
aria-label="Copy code"
data-copied-label="Copied!"
&gt;
&lt;div class="hextra-copy-icon hx:group-[.copied]/copybtn:hidden hx:pointer-events-none hx:h-4 hx:w-4"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="hextra-success-icon hx:hidden hx:group-[.copied]/copybtn:block hx:pointer-events-none hx:h-4 hx:w-4"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/button&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The &lt;code&gt;features&lt;/code&gt; variable is imported from the configuration file we created in step 1. If &lt;code&gt;featureA&lt;/code&gt; is turned on, the component displays a message. Otherwise, it returns &lt;code&gt;null&lt;/code&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Step 3: Implement the feature in Golang&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Next, we need to implement the feature flag in our Golang application. We can do this by checking the value of the flag before executing certain code. For example, we can create a function that only executes if &lt;code&gt;featureB&lt;/code&gt; is turned on:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="hextra-code-block hx:relative hx:mt-6 hx:first:mt-0 hx:group/code"&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;div class="highlight"&gt;&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma"&gt;&lt;code class="language-go" data-lang="go"&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;&lt;span class="kn"&gt;package&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="w"&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="nx"&gt;main&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="w"&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;&lt;span class="w"&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;&lt;span class="w"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="kn"&gt;import&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="w"&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="s"&gt;&amp;#34;github.com/Unleash/unleash-client-go&amp;#34;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="w"&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;&lt;span class="w"&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;&lt;span class="w"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="kd"&gt;func&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="w"&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="nf"&gt;main&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;()&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="w"&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;{&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="w"&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;&lt;span class="w"&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="k"&gt;if&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="w"&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="nx"&gt;unleash&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="nf"&gt;IsEnabled&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="s"&gt;&amp;#34;featureB&amp;#34;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="w"&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;{&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="w"&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;&lt;span class="w"&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="c1"&gt;// Run feature B code&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="w"&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;&lt;span class="w"&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;}&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="w"&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;&lt;span class="w"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;}&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="hextra-code-copy-btn-container hx:opacity-0 hx:transition hx:group-hover/code:opacity-100 hx:flex hx:gap-1 hx:absolute hx:m-[11px] hx:right-0 hx:top-0"&gt;
&lt;button
class="hextra-code-copy-btn hx:group/copybtn hx:cursor-pointer hx:transition-all hx:active:opacity-50 hx:bg-primary-700/5 hx:border hx:border-black/5 hx:text-gray-600 hx:hover:text-gray-900 hx:rounded-md hx:p-1.5 hx:dark:bg-primary-300/10 hx:dark:border-white/10 hx:dark:text-gray-400 hx:dark:hover:text-gray-50"
title="Copy code"
aria-label="Copy code"
data-copied-label="Copied!"
&gt;
&lt;div class="hextra-copy-icon hx:group-[.copied]/copybtn:hidden hx:pointer-events-none hx:h-4 hx:w-4"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="hextra-success-icon hx:hidden hx:group-[.copied]/copybtn:block hx:pointer-events-none hx:h-4 hx:w-4"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/button&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The &lt;code&gt;unleash.IsEnabled()&lt;/code&gt; function is provided by the Unleash client library for Golang. It checks the value of the feature flag and returns &lt;code&gt;true&lt;/code&gt; or &lt;code&gt;false&lt;/code&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Step 4: Integrate with Github Actions&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Finally, we can streamline our feature flagging process by integrating with Github Actions. We can create a workflow that automatically deploys changes to our application when a feature flag is turned on or off. For example, we can create a workflow that deploys changes to our ReactJs application when the &lt;code&gt;config.json&lt;/code&gt; file is updated:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="hextra-code-block hx:relative hx:mt-6 hx:first:mt-0 hx:group/code"&gt;
